  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Key Milestones:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (first US anti-money laundering legislation)\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act (expanded anti-money laundering regulations)\n\n2. Core Legislative Developments:\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- International information sharing frameworks\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n3. Global Regulatory Approaches:\n- Standardized international reporting mechanisms\n- Risk-based compliance frameworks\n- Enhanced technological monitoring systems\n- Cross-border cooperation mechanisms\n\n4. Recent Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency transaction regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction tracking\n- Expanded beneficial ownership transparency\n- Machine learning and AI-assisted detection\n\n5. Sector-Specific Regulations:\n- Banking\n- Real estate\n- Gambling\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Professional services\n\n6. Compliance Mechanisms:\n- Regular risk assessments\n- Comprehensive training programs\n- Internal control systems\n- Independent auditing processes\n\nThe legislative landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
